---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const baseNormalized = base.endsWith('/') ? base : `${base}/`;
const imgBase = `${baseNormalized}images/case-studies/ai-chat/`;
---

<Layout
	title="AI Chat: GitLab Duo & watsonx Code Assistant | Sam Reiss"
	description="Case study: designing AI chat systems for technical users across IBM watsonx Code Assistant and GitLab Duo Chat."
>
	<main>
		<p class="back-link"><a href={import.meta.env.BASE_URL}>Back to homepage</a></p>

		<article class="case-study case-study-rich" lang="en">
			<header class="case-study-header case-study-header-rich" id="case-study-top">
				<p class="section-kicker">Case Study</p>
				<div class="case-study-header-main">
					<h1>Designing AI Chat Systems for Technical Users</h1>
					<p class="case-subtitle">
						From leading the design of IBM watsonx Code Assistant to contributing to GitLab Duo
						Chat, this work explores how chat evolves from a conversational interface into a system
						for action.
					</p>
					<dl class="case-meta-row">
						<div class="case-meta-item">
							<dt>
								<a
									class="case-anchor-link case-anchor-link-meta"
									href="#ibm-watsonx-code-assistant"
									aria-label="Jump to IBM watsonx Code Assistant section"
								>
									IBM watsonx Code Assistant
									<span class="case-anchor-icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true">
										<svg class="case-anchor-icon" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" focusable="false">
											<path
												fill="none"
												stroke="currentColor"
												stroke-width="1.5"
												stroke-linecap="round"
												stroke-linejoin="round"
												d="M3.5 6.5 8 11l4.5-4.5M8 11V2.5"></path>
										</svg>
									</span>
								</a>
							</dt>
							<dd>Lead Designer</dd>
						</div>
						<div class="case-meta-item">
							<dt>
								<a
									class="case-anchor-link case-anchor-link-meta"
									href="#gitlab-duo-chat"
									aria-label="Jump to GitLab Duo Chat section"
								>
									GitLab Duo Chat
									<span class="case-anchor-icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true">
										<svg class="case-anchor-icon" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" focusable="false">
											<path
												fill="none"
												stroke="currentColor"
												stroke-width="1.5"
												stroke-linecap="round"
												stroke-linejoin="round"
												d="M3.5 6.5 8 11l4.5-4.5M8 11V2.5"></path>
										</svg>
									</span>
								</a>
							</dt>
							<dd>Supporting Designer, team of 3 senior designers</dd>
						</div>
						<div class="case-meta-item case-meta-item-wide">
							<dt>Focus</dt>
							<dd>AI chat, developer tools, IDE UX, agent workflows, feedback loops</dd>
						</div>
					</dl>
				</div>
			</header>

			<section class="case-section case-section-rich" aria-labelledby="overview-heading">
				<h2 id="overview-heading">Overview</h2>
				<div class="case-section-body">
					<p class="case-lede">
						I design interaction systems that help technical users understand, control, and
						trust AI-powered workflows.
					</p>
					<p>
						This case study compares two related efforts: IBM watsonx Code Assistant, an
						IDE-integrated coding assistant, and GitLab Duo Chat, a platform chat experience
						evolving toward agents, flows, sessions, and model choice. Together they sit under
						one throughline: designing AI chat systems for technical users across IDE-native and
						platform-native environments.
					</p>
					<div class="focus-grid" role="list">
						<div class="focus-card" role="listitem">
							<h3>Context awareness</h3>
							<p>Chat that understands where the user is working.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="focus-card" role="listitem">
							<h3>Actionability</h3>
							<p>Chat that can move from answering to initiating work.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="focus-card" role="listitem">
							<h3>System coherence</h3>
							<p>Chat that fits into a larger developer workflow.</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section
				class="case-section case-section-rich case-section-product case-section-ibm"
				aria-labelledby="ibm-watsonx-code-assistant"
			>
				<h2 id="ibm-watsonx-code-assistant">
					<a
						class="case-anchor-link case-anchor-link-back"
						href="#case-study-top"
						aria-label="Back to top of case study"
					>
						IBM watsonx Code Assistant
						<span class="case-anchor-icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true">
							<svg class="case-anchor-icon" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" focusable="false">
								<path
									fill="none"
									stroke="currentColor"
									stroke-width="1.5"
									stroke-linecap="round"
									stroke-linejoin="round"
									d="M3.5 9.5 8 5l4.5 4.5M8 5v8.5"></path>
							</svg>
						</span>
					</a>
				</h2>
				<div class="case-section-body case-section-body-ibm-lead">
					<div class="attribution-card attribution-card-lead" role="note">
						<p>
							<strong>Lead designer.</strong> I led the integrated chat experience, partnered
							with engineering and Carbon, delivered the high-fidelity UI, and owned the
							end-to-end design direction for this workstream.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<figure class="case-figure case-figure-editorial case-figure-ibm-lede">
					<div class="case-editorial-media">
						<img
							src={`${imgBase}watsonx-ide-integration.png`}
							alt="watsonx Code Assistant chat panel docked in the IDE beside editor and file tree."
							loading="lazy"
							width="1995"
							height="1228"
						/>
					</div>
					<figcaption>
						IDE-native placement kept chat adjacent to the code users were already editing.
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

				<div class="case-section-body case-section-body-ibm-rest case-section-body-ibm-before-carousel">
					<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Problem</h3>
					<p>
						IBM had existing AI chat explorations, but they were designed for browser-based IBM
						software, not the constraints of an IDE plugin.
					</p>

					<h3 class="case-inline-heading">My role</h3>
					<p>
						I led a team of two UX designers, delivered the high-fidelity design work, partnered
						with engineering, and consulted with the Carbon Design System team.
					</p>

					<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Design challenge</h3>
					<p>
						Adapt Carbon AI chat patterns into a constrained IDE environment while preserving
						brand consistency and continuity with how developers already work.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div
					class="case-carousel case-figure case-figure-editorial case-figure-ibm-carousel"
					data-case-carousel
					role="region"
					aria-roledescription="carousel"
					aria-label="watsonx Code Assistant shipped UI and system views"
					tabindex="0"
				>
						<div class="case-carousel-viewport">
							<div class="case-carousel-track" data-carousel-track>
								<figure class="case-carousel-slide is-active" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="false">
									<div class="case-editorial-media">
										<img
											src={`${imgBase}watsonx-final-chat-ui.png`}
											alt="Shipped watsonx Code Assistant chat interface in the IDE with responses and controls."
											loading="lazy"
											width="1200"
											height="675"
										/>
									</div>
									<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
										The shipped chat UI balanced Carbon alignment with IDE density and developer
										expectations.
									</figcaption>
								</figure>
								<figure class="case-carousel-slide" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="true">
									<div class="case-editorial-media">
										<img
											src={`${imgBase}watsonx-files-and-model-transparency.png`}
											alt="UI showing file references, model selection, and response metadata in chat."
											loading="lazy"
											width="1200"
											height="675"
										/>
									</div>
									<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
										File touches and model visibility made outputs easier to audit and trust.
									</figcaption>
								</figure>
								<figure class="case-carousel-slide" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="true">
									<div class="case-editorial-media">
										<img
											src={`${imgBase}watsonx-session-management.png`}
											alt="Session list and detail views for chat threads in the assistant."
											loading="lazy"
											width="1200"
											height="675"
										/>
									</div>
									<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
										Sessions behaved like trackable units of work, not a flat transcript.
									</figcaption>
								</figure>
								<figure class="case-carousel-slide" data-carousel-slide aria-hidden="true">
									<div class="case-editorial-media">
										<img
											src={`${imgBase}watsonx-code-generation-context.png`}
											alt="Generated code snippet offered inline next to the conversation in the IDE."
											loading="lazy"
											width="1200"
											height="675"
										/>
									</div>
									<figcaption class="case-carousel-figcaption">
										Generated code stayed in context so review, apply, and iterate stayed one gesture
										apart.
									</figcaption>
								</figure>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div class="case-carousel-toolbar">
							<button
								type="button"
								class="case-carousel-btn"
								data-carousel-prev
								aria-label="Previous image"
							>
								<svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 16 16" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false">
									<path
										fill="none"
										stroke="currentColor"
										stroke-width="1.5"
										stroke-linecap="round"
										stroke-linejoin="round"
										d="M10 3 5 8l5 5"></path>
								</svg>
							</button>
							<div class="case-carousel-dots" role="group" aria-label="Choose slide">
								<button
									type="button"
									class="case-carousel-dot is-active"
									data-carousel-dot
									aria-pressed="true"
									aria-label="Slide 1 of 4, shipped chat UI"
								></button>
								<button
									type="button"
									class="case-carousel-dot"
									data-carousel-dot
									aria-pressed="false"
									aria-label="Slide 2 of 4, files and model transparency"
								></button>
								<button
									type="button"
									class="case-carousel-dot"
									data-carousel-dot
									aria-pressed="false"
									aria-label="Slide 3 of 4, session management"
								></button>
								<button
									type="button"
									class="case-carousel-dot"
									data-carousel-dot
									aria-pressed="false"
									aria-label="Slide 4 of 4, code in context"
								></button>
							</div>
							<button
								type="button"
								class="case-carousel-btn"
								data-carousel-next
								aria-label="Next image"
							>
								<svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 16 16" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false">
									<path
										fill="none"
										stroke="currentColor"
										stroke-width="1.5"
										stroke-linecap="round"
										stroke-linejoin="round"
										d="M6 3l5 5-5 5"></path>
								</svg>
							</button>
						</div>
				</div>

				<div class="case-section-body case-section-body-ibm-rest case-section-body-ibm-after-carousel">
					<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Key design decisions</h3>
					<ol class="case-numbered">
						<li>Embedded, non-disruptive chat panel inside the IDE.</li>
						<li>Session management as part of the workflow, not only chat history.</li>
						<li>Feedback controls integrated directly into AI responses.</li>
						<li>
							File handling, generated code, loading states, and model transparency as core
							system behaviors.
						</li>
					</ol>

					<h3 class="case-inline-heading">Outcome</h3>
					<p>
						After launch, the updated chat UI saw an 87% increase in WCA downloads and enabled
						inline feedback collection for the LLM team. Some of the work also informed Carbon
						AI Chat components.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section
				class="case-section case-section-rich case-section-product"
				aria-labelledby="gitlab-duo-chat"
			>
				<h2 id="gitlab-duo-chat">
					<a
						class="case-anchor-link case-anchor-link-back"
						href="#case-study-top"
						aria-label="Back to top of case study"
					>
						GitLab Duo Chat
						<span class="case-anchor-icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true">
							<svg class="case-anchor-icon" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" focusable="false">
								<path
									fill="none"
									stroke="currentColor"
									stroke-width="1.5"
									stroke-linecap="round"
									stroke-linejoin="round"
									d="M3.5 9.5 8 5l4.5 4.5M8 5v8.5"></path>
							</svg>
						</span>
					</a>
				</h2>
				<div class="case-section-body">
					<div class="attribution-card attribution-card-support" role="note">
						<p>
							<strong>Systems contribution.</strong> I was not the sole lead. I contributed as
							one of three senior designers supporting Duo Chat, helping shape interaction
							patterns, workflow concepts, and system coherence. This section reflects
							collaborative design support, not single-owner leadership.
						</p>
					</div>

					<p>
						At GitLab, chat was evolving from a conversational assistant into an orchestration
						layer for agents, sessions, flows, and model choice. I partnered on how those pieces
						showed up in the product surface so users could follow work from prompt to outcome.
					</p>

					<section class="gitlab-module" aria-labelledby="gitlab-a">
						<h3 id="gitlab-a">A. Sessions as units of work</h3>
						<figure class="case-figure">
							<div class="case-media-slot">
								<img
									src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-session-details.png`}
									alt=""
									loading="lazy"
									width="1200"
									height="675"
								/>
								<p class="case-media-fallback">
									<code>gitlab-duo-session-details.png</code>
									<span class="case-media-hint">
										Add to <code>public/images/case-studies/ai-chat/</code>
									</span>
								</p>
							</div>
							<figcaption>
								Sessions read less like passive chat history and more like trackable units of
								agentic work, with status, recency, and clear entry points into details.
							</figcaption>
						</figure>
					</section>

					<section class="gitlab-module" aria-labelledby="gitlab-b">
						<h3 id="gitlab-b">B. Starting from suggested prompts</h3>
						<div class="case-figure-grid">
							<figure class="case-figure">
								<div class="case-media-slot">
									<img
										src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-suggestions-panel.png`}
										alt=""
										loading="lazy"
										width="1200"
										height="675"
									/>
									<p class="case-media-fallback">
										<code>gitlab-duo-suggestions-panel.png</code>
										<span class="case-media-hint">
											Add to <code>public/images/case-studies/ai-chat/</code>
										</span>
									</p>
								</div>
								<figcaption>Suggestions panel: contextually relevant starting points.</figcaption>
							</figure>
							<figure class="case-figure">
								<div class="case-media-slot">
									<img
										src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-empty-state.png`}
										alt=""
										loading="lazy"
										width="1200"
										height="675"
									/>
									<p class="case-media-fallback">
										<code>gitlab-duo-empty-state.png</code>
										<span class="case-media-hint">
											Add to <code>public/images/case-studies/ai-chat/</code>
										</span>
									</p>
								</div>
								<figcaption>Empty state: reducing blank-page friction at chat entry.</figcaption>
							</figure>
						</div>
					</section>

					<section class="gitlab-module" aria-labelledby="gitlab-c">
						<h3 id="gitlab-c">C. From chat to action</h3>
						<figure class="case-figure">
							<div class="case-media-slot">
								<img
									src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-slash-command-invoke.png`}
									alt=""
									loading="lazy"
									width="1200"
									height="675"
								/>
								<p class="case-media-fallback">
									<code>gitlab-duo-slash-command-invoke.png</code>
									<span class="case-media-hint">
										Add to <code>public/images/case-studies/ai-chat/</code>
									</span>
								</p>
							</div>
							<figcaption>
								Slash commands helped trigger structured flows, confirm intent, and spin up a
								running session from a single deliberate action.
							</figcaption>
						</figure>
					</section>

					<section class="gitlab-module" aria-labelledby="gitlab-d">
						<h3 id="gitlab-d">D. Model and mode clarity</h3>
						<div class="case-figure-grid">
							<figure class="case-figure">
								<div class="case-media-slot">
									<img
										src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-model-switcher.png`}
										alt=""
										loading="lazy"
										width="1200"
										height="675"
									/>
									<p class="case-media-fallback">
										<code>gitlab-duo-model-switcher.png</code>
										<span class="case-media-hint">
											Add to <code>public/images/case-studies/ai-chat/</code>
										</span>
									</p>
								</div>
								<figcaption>Model switcher: which model is active without crowding the composer.</figcaption>
							</figure>
							<figure class="case-figure">
								<div class="case-media-slot">
									<img
										src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-classic-chat-switcher.png`}
										alt=""
										loading="lazy"
										width="1200"
										height="675"
									/>
									<p class="case-media-fallback">
										<code>gitlab-duo-classic-chat-switcher.png</code>
										<span class="case-media-hint">
											Add to <code>public/images/case-studies/ai-chat/</code>
										</span>
									</p>
								</div>
								<figcaption>Classic chat switcher: clarity when modes diverge.</figcaption>
							</figure>
						</div>
					</section>

					<section class="gitlab-module" aria-labelledby="gitlab-e">
						<h3 id="gitlab-e">E. Agent selection and specialization</h3>
						<figure class="case-figure">
							<div class="case-media-slot">
								<img
									src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-agent-switching.png`}
									alt=""
									loading="lazy"
									width="1200"
									height="675"
								/>
								<p class="case-media-fallback">
									<code>gitlab-duo-agent-switching.png</code>
									<span class="case-media-hint">
										Add to <code>public/images/case-studies/ai-chat/</code>
									</span>
								</p>
							</div>
							<figcaption>
								Specialized agents needed to be discoverable and understandable from inside the
								chat surface, not buried in settings.
							</figcaption>
						</figure>
					</section>

					<section class="gitlab-module" aria-labelledby="gitlab-f">
						<h3 id="gitlab-f">F. Feedback loop</h3>
						<figure class="case-figure">
							<div class="case-media-slot">
								<img
									src={`${imgBase}gitlab-duo-feedback-mechanism.png`}
									alt=""
									loading="lazy"
									width="1200"
									height="675"
								/>
								<p class="case-media-fallback">
									<code>gitlab-duo-feedback-mechanism.png</code>
									<span class="case-media-hint">
										Add to <code>public/images/case-studies/ai-chat/</code>
									</span>
								</p>
							</div>
							<figcaption>
								Lightweight feedback gave users a response to imperfect outputs and helped teams
								improve model quality over time.
							</figcaption>
						</figure>
					</section>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="case-section case-section-rich case-section-close" aria-labelledby="learned-heading">
				<h2 id="learned-heading">What this work taught me</h2>
				<div class="case-section-body">
					<p class="case-pullquote">
						Across both products, the most important design problem was not simply where to place
						a chat box. It was how to make AI feel situated, controllable, and useful inside real
						technical user workflows.
					</p>
					<ul class="case-takeaways">
						<li>AI chat needs context: anchoring to files, tasks, and session state.</li>
						<li>
							Users need clear control over models, agents, sessions, and actions before they will
							rely on automation.
						</li>
						<li>
							Trust comes from visibility, feedback, confirmation, and reversibility, not from
							polish alone.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</section>
		</article>
	</main>
</Layout>

<style>
	.case-study-rich {
		max-width: 980px;
		margin-inline: auto;
		font-family: "Work Sans", Inter, "Helvetica Neue", Arial, sans-serif;
	}

	.case-study-header-rich {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: minmax(170px, 0.46fr) 1fr;
		gap: 2.5rem;
		padding-bottom: 2.9rem;
		border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
		margin-bottom: 0;
	}

	.case-study-header-rich .section-kicker {
		grid-column: 1;
		font-size: 1.38rem;
		font-weight: 600;
		letter-spacing: -0.01em;
		color: #111;
		margin: 0;
		padding-top: 0.58rem;
	}

	.case-study-header-main {
		grid-column: 2;
		min-width: 0;
	}

	.case-study-header-rich h1 {
		font-family: "Instrument Serif", Georgia, "Times New Roman", serif;
		font-size: clamp(2.7rem, 4.7vw, 4.4rem);
		font-weight: 400;
		line-height: 1.02;
		letter-spacing: -0.014em;
		max-width: 22ch;
		margin: 0 0 1.1rem;
	}

	.case-subtitle {
		color: #242424;
		font-size: clamp(1.05rem, 1.35vw, 1.18rem);
		line-height: 1.62;
		letter-spacing: -0.008em;
		max-width: 62ch;
		margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
	}

	.case-anchor-link {
		display: inline-flex;
		align-items: baseline;
		gap: 0.22em;
		max-width: 100%;
		color: inherit;
		text-decoration: none;
		transition: color 160ms ease;
	}

	.case-anchor-link:hover {
		color: #0a0a0a;
	}

	.case-anchor-link:focus-visible {
		outline: 2px solid var(--foreground);
		outline-offset: 3px;
		border-radius: 2px;
	}

	.case-anchor-icon-wrap {
		display: inline-flex;
		flex-shrink: 0;
		translate: 0 0.12em;
		opacity: 0.55;
